<Review>Good vibes all around! When I arrived, I was greeted by Craig, who warmly gave me a quick tour around the studio. The space itself is bright and clean, with a modern flair. There's a warm-up area up front, and then a darker room where the circuit-training happens. In the back, there are lockers and bathrooms. We took a 45-minute FIT class with Tiffany on a Tuesday morning. The class consisted of a warm-up followed by 3 stations with 3 activities each that we looped through 3 times each. After circuit-training, we concluded with an ab workout on the mats, which was quite strenuous too (I had been expecting to just end with stretches). I also really appreciated how well-ventilated the room was - when we were wrapping up, there was extra air cooling the room, which made it very refreshing. Overall, the workout was well-organized and sufficiently challenging! Tiffany was upbeat, engaging, and full of positive energy - we  really enjoyed our WOLA experience!</Review>< pictures>

I attended this church back in the 80's when it was located in Ingelwood and it was the very reason I strayed from God and Our Lord and Savior Jesus Christ. I was very young at the time and had gone through some devastating events. I was seeking comfort in the Lord and was baptized there but was told that if I did not speak in tongues that I would not be recognized by God or as a member of the church, hence when it did not happen I was shunned. Unlike some of you, I was not greeted very warmly and frankly, Pastor's message was not delivered very kind or loving and I believe in the truth and speaking directly from the Holy Bible. Of course I am older and have since been called back to the Lord, have been saved by full water immersion, enrolled in Theology and Seminary School, participate in Missionary work, and have been lead to a beautiful and loving church lead by strong and anointed leaders that work tirelessly to connect people to Jesus Christ, that teach the gospel from the Holy Bible which does not include guilt and shame. This was a young church when I first attended so I hope Pastor has grown in his methods of teaching because again I state it was because of you I was turned off from Christianity. I praise God for leading me back to Christ Jesus and creating in me a grateful and faithful follower.< /Review>

<name>Rudy Ornelas<//name>< Date>
1518303075218<//Date>
< rating>
5</rating>
< text>
Cancun juice is the place for some real unique Mexican food with hint health congest items. Of course it depends on the meal. You can get some chicken taquitos alright serving is really tasting and you totally don't feel guilty :). The star is their burrito at about 6ish with tax is by far one the best breakfast burritos I've had in my life. This is not the Mexican burrito you eat and it fills you all day. The egg, bean, bacon and ham were cooked just right. It was so good! I kind of regret not adding a freshly squeezed orange juice. Their Carne Asada Torta with a side of fried banana  & strawberry with  3 leches icing is so good! The place is always clean and the manager is always attentive of the customer needs. Oh yeah, the green salsa is really good goes great with any meal from there.<//text>

< Review>
Tenants had just moved out of my rental, giving me the opportunity to consider selling. To help make the re-rent or sell decision, I needed estimates for any repair work that would help sell the house. I began by calling Advanced IPM for a pest inspection.

The inspector checked for dry rot by poking a metal-tipped pole into suspicious areas of siding, eaves, window sills, etc. The metal tip left a hole the size of a pencil eraser, just enough to be noticeable, but small enough not to require repair in the event of re-renting.

Later in the day, I received a call from Advanced IPM informing me that the inspector had been ‚Äúlet go,‚Äù and ‚ÄúAnother inspector will be out tomorrow.‚Äù

The new inspector, ‚ÄúJ,‚Äù marked areas of dry rot much differently: when he found indications of rot, he poked his pole into the wood, then gave it a sudden twist, popping out a chunk. The divots he created were large and unsightly enough that, should I decide to re-rent, I‚Äôd have to repair the damage. I wasn‚Äôt happy. He also missed dry rot in the rear eave that the ‚Äúlet go‚Äù inspector had noted.
I decided to sell. After all repairs were completed, I called Advanced IPM for a re-inspection. While J checked the repairs, I asked why he popped out chunks of wood. His reply: ‚ÄúSo if we get the job, my crew can identify the dry rot,‚Äù a ridiculous answer, since his own pest report showed the exact locations of dry rot. J said he‚Äôd send a clearance report the next day. A week later --- no clearance. I called and asked a staff member to send it.

When the property sold, the buyer asked for a Home Inspection. The inspector found a three-foot-long area of dry rot in plain sight next to the chimney and another above the garage door. Fortunately, California has a Structural Pest Control Board which takes consumer complaints seriously, and Advanced IPM repaired and painted the missed areas at no cost.
J unnecessarily damaged my property, gave an unbelievable reason for doing so, missed three areas of dry rot, and didn‚Äôt send a clearance as promised.

I won‚Äôt be calling Advanced IPM again.</Review>

Union City isn't my usual stomping ground but I was in the area with a few hours to kill and an unruly mop of hair on my head. D&R popped up on my search and I decided to take a chance. Boy am I glad I did. I didn't have an appointment so I had to wait about 30 minutes but the haircut and friendly service was well worth the wait. I ended up with Jeremy (second chair from the door on the right) and he did a fantastic job.  I might have to accidentally end up in Union City again in about 6-8 week. Tips: make an appointment and bring cash.</review>

<user_id>111156761225238961827<//user_id><user_name>Krista H Renella< /user_name><date>1528690463883< /date><rating>3<//rating><review>I hate to say, but every time I hope that I've finally stumbled upon an authentic and delicious Mexican restaurant sadly I am disappointed. I got the Crab Enchiladas, with a Chile Relleno on the side. The crab tasted like it had been from a can or frozen. It was rough and hair-like. The sauce on the enchilada was overwhelmingly liquidy. <userid>101329839098330939746<//userid><name>Burton Hunter<//name>< date>
1516944376311</date>
<Rating>4<//Rating>< text>
Really good tasting Mexican-style food dishes.  They have a some of their own recipes that are super-delicious.
If you want beef, try their "shredded beef",
If chicken is your choice, their "grilled chicken" dishes are best.  2 of my favorites.
Seafood is always a bit more expensive, but try their Campachana Appetizer Platter  to share with a group.  (It has Campachana seafood ingredients, but cooked as their own special recipe.  My personal favorite of this dish is all the seafood ingredients, each saut√©ed to perfection using garlic-infused oil. & delicious!  My brother , from Portland, Oregon enjoys quality restaurant food. I ordered this & tried it on him.  He commented to the waiter that it was the best tasting restaurant food dish that he'd had in at least 10 years.  They do this dish to perfection!

One caveat on this dish: if the season ocean waters are warm, then the restaurant can only legally purchase oysters that have been pasturized (partially pre-cooked).  If the oysters are pasturized, it spoils their taste -really bad! (don't get the oysters if they've been pasturized: ONLY in THAT season, have them leave out the oysters and substitute more of one of the other ingredients).
If it's been cooler and the small oysters are NOT pasturized, DO get them - broiled on the half-shell with garlic oil (Yum!)

Many of their delicious sauces are made in-house.  Their pico-de-gallo is a treat, assembled with fresh ingredients when you order it.  Order this when they first seat you & they'll bring it out to enjoy with their house-fried table chips.  Nothing mushy or blah about this Pico-de-gallo; it is deliciously fresh at Laura's.
I love this treasured little hole-in-the-wall place.  It's been around & popular for years - and for good reason: delicious food !  AND at a good price!<//text>

< Review>
This is a little mom and pop restaurant. I've been here a few times when I want to get something quick and authentic. The shredded beef tostadas are to die for. They are a huge serving so if you are hungry get one. My son has had their cheese burger with fries and let me just tell you that this burger is really tasty. I've also had the 2 item combo with a chile relleno, beef enchilada and Mexican rice and refried beans also a very good dish oh and it come with a soup or salad I picked the Albondiga(meat ball) soup. The albondiga soup is very delicious and packed with vegies. My friend had the carne asada quesadilla and it was HUGE! comes with rice guacamole and sour cream. If you are in the neighborhood and want a quick Mexican bite come to Laura's.</Review>

< Review>
Our home was in desperate need of a remodel, it needed everything, new roof, flooring, re wire,  re plumb, four bathrooms, game room and a kitchen. Basically our home was a gut job.  I had been dreaming of a remodel for years. Needless to say we were nervous about hiring a company that could handle such a big project. After talking to numerous contractors I was becoming discouraged, no real quotes and no time lines.  Then I discovered Treeium and knew I had found a company that I could trust with a 1/2 million Dollar renovation.
Shahar Algazy has been nothing short of amazing, treating our home like his own and diligently keeping everything on time and on budget, if not Below.  Everyday since we began Shahar has had a 10 man crew on the job, practically unheard  of with most companies. When it came time to upgrade the electric panel we were faced with the possible need to destroy a large portion of  our yard and cut down a  beautiful and stately tree that is a major feature in our yard. Shahar could have left it at that but he went the extra  mile to find a better solution. Shahar saved us 30K and our beloved ficus tree.
We continue to be impressed with Treeium's customer service and communication. The Treeium portal is very easy to navigate and keeps everything clear and organized. We love the gallery that lets our friends and family keep track of the  progress. Great work Treeium and Shahar Algazy for talking such good care of our home and helping us make our remodel dreams come true.
Sincerely, Kristen Shadburn</Review>

< text>
This was my first remodel so I researched and met with several companies before deciding to contract with Treeium to do my bathroom remodel. My project manager was Jacke Mair. When Jacke and I first met for the initial consultation, he was very friendly and answered all of my questions. He was very personable, respectful, and upfront with me. He didn't attempt to "sell" me on doing what I didn't want done nor did he pressure me to do business with the company. We had a good rapport, I felt comfortable with him especially since I wasn't going to be home when they started working on the bathroom and he was honest with me along the way.

During the remodeling process, Jacke Mair continued communication with me via calling/texting to let me know what was being done while I was at work. As things arose beyond his and my control while working on the bathroom (i.e. rotten beams and no insulation--My house is over 90years old so hey it was inevitable ) He worked his magic to keep the price as low as he could and did some things at no additional charge for me which I'm so grateful for since I am new to remodeling my home. The work done was per our contract with what I wanted done and with what Jacke advised needed to get done for the bathroom to be up to code. Even when I would occasionally add more things for him to do he would offer great suggestions on what would be best to make the bathroom look great.  Everything was in writing so neither of us would forget what needed to happen for this project. We even referenced the contract during the remodeling to be sure everything was being done.

I even asked if Jacke could have his team install a storage cabinet for me in my other bathroom (outside the scope of our contract) and he was able to get that done for me at no charge. Now I can store my stuff in there too. It looks really nice.

The workers were friendly I didn't have much of an issue with them. Jacke Mair made sure the floors were covered so know damage would be done to my floors since I have hardwood floors throughout the house. He also provided a porto-potty so the workers would not use my bathroom as they worked which I appreciated. However, I didn't' care for the materials being left outside (even when the weather was bad) instead of being stored in the garage. The garage was difficult to open but just needed a little "elbow grease" to open but the new materials were not harmed which was most important.

All of the work done was by the book, up to code and no corners cut. It was great quality and well worth the price and time it took to get done. I don't even want to use the bathroom lol . I just want to have it for decoration.
Jacke Mair went above and beyond working on my project and I am so pleased with the outcome. He was more than willing to do all he could to make sure I was pleased and happy...and I AM!

The financing department was really nice. They answered my questions about the options they offered and was even available to answer questions after the project was over via phone/email.<//text>

<Time>1581529781702</Time>< text>
Three years ago, Treeium made renovation in our house. We were happy with their work until a crack developed between an old wall and new development.  We also found that a glass shower door is displaced a little bit but enough to affect its operation.  I contacted Gina Cada from Treeium.  She told me that our warranty has been expired but they want to do what they can to satisfy their client. She asked Gregory Knemeyer from Treeium Quality Assurance Department to make inspection of the issues and give me recommendation. Gregory came and made thorough inspection. He checked not only the issues I mentioned, but found a few more minor defects, which developed after renovation.  He told that the issues can be fixed, and most likely, Treeium will send their people to do the job. Then he arranged fixing the shower door with the subcontractor (who made the door installation). They came and fixed the door.  Gregory came by himself to fix the other issues. He spent more than half a day and fixed all problems. It was a pleasure to see how he works, thoroughly and accurately. Thank you, Gregory, very much! Despite that our warranty expired, Treeium did not charge me for this work. Thank you, Treeium, thank you Gina!<//text>

< text>
We interviewed 7 contractors to work on my dad's home remodel. We had such a very, very bad experience a couple of years ago with our own house that I could not put my 91 y/o dad through the same. You would think that 7 was over kill, but in the end there was only 2 real contenders. His home is over 60 yrs old and we had no idea what's going to happen once they started. I wanted a company with experience, expertise and enough crews to get the job done. I actually picked the other company, but Treeium's Shahar Algazy was very diligent, persistent and actually came down significantly to meet my price from his original bid. Treeium has lots to offer because of their size. You can tell they cater to their customers. Love their customer portal, no other company had this. All contracts, change orders, documents and payments are through the portal. It stores everything, so you can track progress, payments, balance. There is even a photo gallery that all of their crews can upload pictures of the project, so no question on what's going on. Also helps if you're traveling during project. We did have major issues once they started on a relatively easy bathroom project. There was a fresh water leak that had been there for years and a lot of unsafe electrical connections throughout the house. A big concern since we are trying to bring my 91 y/o mom home to be with dad during their last years. Money was running low, so Shahar referred me to their finance staff. Treeium helped in a huge way because they offered a "same as cash" retail installment loan which funded $45K to finish the project. Approved within minutes. We needed fast cash because our re-finance was going to take over 30 days to complete. If you payoff within 12 mos, no monthly payment, no interest. Can't beat that. Can't say enough about Shahar. Answers and sends text all the time. Very trusting and compassionate. Easy to talk to even with when issues come up. He understands and had much patience with my father. He treated him like family and made sure that all crews did the same. They ended up doing major work on the house, my dad refused to leave until the last minute, so everyone did their best to keep the work areas safe for him to stay as long as he could. Didn't plan all this extra work, but they proved that it was necessary and so glad that we chose Treeium. Can't imagine if we would have selected another or smaller company! We are going to use them for some work on our house and so is my sister.<//text>

<username>Karen Williams<//username><Review>I have had experience with one other "5" star company and all I can say is not all 5 star companies are the same on Home Advisor. She brought samples of cabinet finishes, back splashes and paint to go with the countertops we had discussed with Liran. During demolition the crew discovered the outside kitchen wall was soaking wet. The wall board and insulation was removed and Liran was called. When our new shower was turned on, the water was running down the wall from a broken drain pipe that had been caused by another "5" star company when they replaced the upstairs shower and plumbing a few weeks before. I can't imagine what the damage would have been if we had waited the 3 years to remodel the kitchen as originally planned. Liran came right over to assess the situation and got the repairs done ASAP. <Date>1548385395677<//Date><Rating>4< /Rating><Review>We still have several ongoing projects with Treeium. It's perfect for our need being a large company they offer finance options we can take advantage of. This review would be for the complete bathroom remodel. They have different person(s) that take care of different phase of the remodeling. The demo went well and took care of covering and protecting the washer and dryer, the hotmop was done right at the end, though I wished they had taped the door like I asked to keep the smell away from the rest of the house. Tiling was excellent, but it was explained to us that it couldn't be as flushed because the tile is not flushed..., what do I know. Our project manager Aviv aswered all our calls and text even through the evening since we could only visit the hardware store in the evening after work to go over the project with him. The project took longer than expected because sometimes the worker forgot or should've known but didn't know to bring things they need for their job, such as not having to wait an extra week to make use of our new toilet becasue they didn't have the seal after they installed it. Yes, these seem to be small issues and there were others, they did come back to fixed the issues. Being this is the first time we work with a contractor, we didn't know what to expect, but it's been a good learning experience. Treeium is a good company since they make sure they get the job done right at the end. What have we learned: 1. We will personally mark each item/area to be demo before they do the actual demo! 2. 2</Rating>
< text>
updated:5/13/18

CRMC in Fresno is supposedly a "tier 1", premier hospital in California's San Joaquin Valley. Not exactly sure how this is determined, but I'm guessing there is some shady exchange of cash for the title. That being said, below is a pros/cons list from a custome... er, patient.

Pros:
-Registered Nurses (RNs) and Patient Care Assistants (PCAs). These folks take on a VAST majority of the workload. In my experience, at least 4 out of 5 of them clearly enjoy helping people. Most of them work 12hr+ shifts and I have yet to hear them complain, regardless of often being understaffed and greatly underpaid.

-Free WiFi. (when it works)

Cons:
-Waiting Times. In my experience, it has taken 3 days of laying on a gurney in a hallway before getting moved to a room. It's not horrible, as there are the wonderful aforementioned RNs to tend to your ailments, but it is uncomfortable to say the least and you will undoubtedly be sore rounding mid second day.

-Cafeteria Staff. The folks working in the lobby cafeteria are some of the rudest and least helpful staff onsite. Specifically one of the morning cashiers (an elderly, Asian lady who immediately threw my food in the rubbish bin when I asked her if I could step aside to get the proper change together) Another instance, I asked a server a question about one of the items at the hot food station and was told "it's self serve!" as she turned and walked away.

-Blue Sky Dining. This is the patient in room dining department at CRMC. They have two "specials" for each meal and an additional selection of options with each meal. If you get your meal as ordered, consider yourself very lucky. I ordered a mushroom omelet and side of fruit, but was given pancakes and turkey sausage. Any deviations from their "specials" will result in unwanted results.
(on a side note, you can always have food delivered by an outside restaurant, in lieu of the hospital options)

-Communication. There doesn't seem to be much communication, if any, between departments or sometimes even within the same department. Be prepared to answer the same questions two or three times a day for the duration of your stay. It gets irritating quickly.

-Noise/Lack of sleep. Unless you have a contagious disease you will have a roommate. This could range from someone who was in some some sort of accident and sleeps most of the time to a violent junkie in handcuffs who screams and yells all day and all night.

Summary: CRMC Fresno should be able to get the job done, but if you have other options look into them. Research, research, research.

Cheers< /text>
</record>
</dataset><record>

<date>1529598855118</date>< review>
One reason you should go anywhere else

Locked down ER on a daily basis.

That means if you have a family member waiting with you and they go on lockdown because they have too many people in the ER your family member must go wait in a completely separate building.
This means you will sit alone (sick or in pain?) for a very extended long wait time and once you do get a room in back or bed in the hallway or like I got a chair that barely reclines, your family member still cannot come back and stay with you. I can't speak for everyone with chronic illness but I know that when I'm going through it there's nothing I need more than my family support so it's worth it to me to go anywhere else.
Funny I find very few reviews that mention this lockdown but it upsets the majority of the ER when it happens. Especially the non-english speakers that don't understand they must leave their family member sick.
Think about that.........

<gmap_id>0x80945e0a451bde4b:0xe6319ba89de3ea4d< /gmap_id><Time>1464302698558</Time>< review>
I went to CRMC with what I knew was bronchitis. They did give me a nebulizer treatment and some inhalers, which only helped with the weezing and none of the other bronchitis symptoms. I've had bronchitis before and it can be horribly debilitating, especially the longer it goes untreated. The doctors claimed that they weren't going to give me antibiotics because of supposed side effects. They wouldn't even prescribe me anything for the cough. I had to spend money out of pocket for cold and flu medications which did not work. The coughing was so frequent that I couldn't sleep or eat. I have had surgery on my head and the constant coughing was causing problems with that too. I had to basically drink Dayquil and Nyquil to even be able to stand up right. I was in the process of moving too which I had to do with bronchitis, pneumonia, and no medication on a hot day in Fresno. That's right CRMC missed the pneumonia even after taking x-rays of my chest and me going to the emergency room. After arriving in Monterey, I immediately went to the emergency room and they found the pneumonia and bronchitis right away, and immediately prescribed me a Z-pack (antibiotics) and an rx for the cough that gave me immediate relief. Oh, did I forget to mention that the nurse refused to look at the list of pharmacies right in front of her? Of course I couldn't remember the street that my pharmacy was on, I had very little sleep, very little food, and no medication for days. She asked if I was homeless since I didn't know the street name! What the hell does that have to with how you treat or address people?!</review>

<date>1551777527771<//date><Rating>3</Rating><text>Little Caesars is that "hit and miss" more times then none you know what you're getting into when you're deciding to get Little Caesars then deciding to spend twice as much at a regular pizza place. Depending on what location you decide to go to in town will effect on how your pizza looks. My spouse and I used to go to the drive thru one we have in town due to convenience and it's not as crowded as the one in Mary's Vineyard, yes.. you heard me right.. This place actually gets crowded. But I can see why, pizza is affordable and you can by in bulk to feed many. Plus the overall flavor isn't bad. I feel like this kind of pizza is really good if someone brings it to you rather then you actually paying for it yourself. It's the saying "free food is good food", that definitely applies here. The deep dish pizzas are really good! But super greasy so bring some extra napkins with you. On a different note: the Pizza Portal needs to be fixed. The premise is great! Walk up, put the number they provided you with in the kiosk, grab your stuff and go. But it's hard to do when they don't actually use the kiosk so when you show up, no pizza in the kiosk, so you have to wait in line now for something you tried to get done through this new and faster invention. < review>
The pizza isn't to bad if you call & order over the phone but don't count on getting the full order (even if you called & your order take's 30 minutes, it's never done when they say it'll be done, nor is the whole order ready or done right!)
